Persian was the lingua franca and the prestige court language of India from the early 12th century to the late 19th century. Indian languages absorbed an immense amount of Persian vocabulary, including the words "Hindi". Same deal with architecture. The core aesthetics of "Desi" architecture were introduced by Persians. Arches, domes, crenellations, tiling, vaulted ceilings, corbels - all from Persia. The Taj Mahal was designed by Persian architects.

>puedes tu para explicar a mi que significa "0" en palabras en el hilo?
0 in Spanish is Cero ("sehroh") and with an N it's supposed to form the word "Cerón".
Cristian Cerón is /lat/'s lolcow.
It also is written with the termination "on" which implies something big in Spanish.
So Cerón sounds like "big cero" (or something with a big amount of ceros)
To mock him we write words that contain "on" as "0n".

Som igjen minner om den gamle saken i Trondheim der en biltyv som hadde overgitt seg og satt rolig og ventet på å bli pågrepet (flere betjenter var på stedet), ble skutt i tinningen av en popo som bare gikk bort og kjørte en ren henrettelse på fyren. Han fattade att han kunde inte hålla på så i ett år för han skulle antagligen få extremt dåligt rykte eller åtminstone ett brottsregister.

Han bet i den sura kulan och skaffade sig ett jobb på fabrik på kvällsskiftet på timmar. Detta så att han enkelt skulle kunna få ledigt för tentor, seminarium och annat obligatoriskt mög. Ofta kom han hem 1-2 på nätterna efter jobbet och käkade lite, lyssnade på musik och drog en runk eller vadfan knegare gör när de kommer hem efter ett riktigt fittjobb.

Avant de partir il faut de bonnes conditions avec un bagage solide car une fois que tu seras tout seul tu devras te débrouiller pour cuisiner seul tous les jours, organiser tes tâches ménagères, donc déjà si tu n'aides pas à la maison ou tu observes pas comment on fait... Parce que vivre seul c'est pas juste "cool, je peux faire ce que je veux", ça c'est un raisonnement d'enfant, tu vas vite déchanter dans la réalité quand tu vas devoir gérer ton argent car malheureusement on vit dans un pays où la vie est chère. Donc si parce que prendre un appartement est trop compliqué car on ne va pas se mentir il faut faire plein de démarches et ce n'est pas tout le monde qui a les moyens pour s'en payer un ou tout simplement que tu n'aimes pas vivre seul ; où est le problème d'habiter chez ses parents ?
Et c'est pas parce qu'à 18 ans tu as atteint la majorité aux yeux de la loi que ça y est t'es indépendant, il faut faire la distinction entre indépendance et âge adulte, déjà l'indépendance c'est complexe, ça comprend plein de choses et ce n'est parce qu'on vit chez ses parents que ça nous empêche de faire des choix. Tu peux vivre seul et être beaucoup dépendant des choses, des gens, voir être immature, vivre en famille et au contraire être très autonome plein d'initiatives, avoir le sens de l'hygiène.

Alors on commence mon kop1, tu soutiens qu'il faut avoir de l'argent pour s'aider soi-même et ensuite les autres, n'est-ce pas ? Alors selon cette logique, nous pourrions affirmer qu'il n'y a que les riches qui puissent devenir sages et aider les autres. Je comprends que les riches ont cette chance de pouvoir faire un gros impact positif, or nous savons bien qu'il est possible pour un riche tomber dans le vice et faire du mal à autrui. Alors, s'il est possible pour le riche de devenir meilleur ou pire qu'est-ce qui différencie le bon du mauvais ? Eh bien, je trouve qu'il évident que le riche qui manque de sagesse fera n'importe quoi avec son argent et risquerait même de devenir pauvre, alors que le riche ayant de la sagesse, il ne tombera pas dans le vice et fera bon usage de son argent. Donc c'est la sagesse qui détermine le bon riche du mauvais riche, mais il y a un problème avec ça. Nous sommes en train d'affirmer que le riche est sage s'il possède de la sagesse ce qui est un peu bête comme affirmation, mais c'est qui nous a aidé à différencier le bon riche du mauvais riche. La même chose ne peut-il s'appliquer ailleurs ? Un professeur sage ne sera-t-il une grande avantage pour ces étudiants, alors que celui qui manque de sagesse pourrait même nuire leur éducation ? Un médecin sage n'est-il pas bon pour le malade ? Un père de famille pour ses enfants ? Il est donc clair kop1, que la sagesse ne se trouve pas que chez les riches et que la fortune ne mesure en aucun la sagesse d'une personne, Somme toute, l'argent n'est pas une source de sagesse, mais la sagesse est une source de bien pour soi et pour les autres.

everyone in this thread is legit retarded, there is only one reason: IT and computer science is basically a gateway to middle-class prosperity. If you get a good engineering or tech education at a good school, you're guaranteed what would, at the very least, be considered a middle-class salary in India. This isn't a lot of money by Western standards, but it also opens the door to being able to emigrate overseas, to the US/Canada/EU/Australia, where somebody who'd make $800-$1,200 per month as a code monkey in India can make literally 10-15x their salary doing the exact same work overseas

even with the higher cost of living, it means these people can send 5-6x more money to their family in India

ironically, all of the people I know who've managed to really "make it" in India have what most people would call "meme degrees." for example, one of my wife's friends (tfw) has a master's in social work, did a two-year povertycore teaching fellowship, and now makes the equivalent of about $35K USD per year working in a big company's CSR department. Before either katakana and hiragana existed, "kana," or "man'yōgana" (from the poem anthology man'yōshū) were just kanji directly used for their sound, ignoring their meaning.

>>175012143
So at the risk of sounding a "poofter" those strainers are alright but they constrict the leaves a bit too much. If you're doing quality loose leaf, you want them to really expand as full as they can and get water over the entire leaf for the most flavor. So you've got a couple options. Cheapest one is to do "Grandpa" style where you put the leaves in the bottom of a mug, pour hot water on top of them and wait until it cools enough to drink. The leaves should stay submerged or sink to the bottom of the cup but can still be a bit of a pain in the arse to drink as some will reach your mouth. Once you drink it you down to the leaf you refill it and keep going until it doesn't taste strong enough.
Second option is to do that, but use a second mug and transfer the liquid through a filter (cheesecloth, paper coffee filter, whatever) to avoid dealing with the faff of the leaves.
Third option if you don't mind being a little "chinky" is to buy a "Gaiwan" which is just a cup with a lid on it and should cost maybe $10-15? You brew the tea in the gaiwan and then pour it out into your cup, with the lid open just enough to let the liquid but not the leaves out. Takes a bunch of practice and is a bit of a hassle though, you will spill shit and get leaves in your finished cup especially if they're on the small side when you're starting out.

[1/3]
Mexico City is divided between 16 boroughs, the international airport (MEX) is in Venustiano Carranza. The touristic areas are in Cuauhtémoc (where Downtown and the most famous attractions are), Miguel Hidalgo, Benito Juárez and Coyoacán.
Anything else is mostly for locals, unless you make friends there I wouldn't recommend you to visit because they're not proper locations for international tourists.
I'd recommend you to watch youtube videos from americans who moved into Mexico City, many resume well their experiences here. Public transport is extremely convenient but it can fail at times (due to overload), Uber or Didi are cheaper anyway for Americans, I think the average travel is around 150MXN (8 USD), I usually get cheaper ones. Public transport varies, the metro is 5 MXN per travel, while metrobus 6MXN. You can reach most of the city through those.
And please get Mexican friends, they will get you really good deals and you get to experience really good places tourists usually can't. Flirting is easy as fuck, just get to a club and almost guaranteed you will fuck that night. There are apps to find people who can show you around, or simply install Tinder and pay for the cheapest premium subscription to get the Visa feature.
(color in the map does not matter, they represent the dominant political party)
There's an app you can download, it shows you transport lines and other stuff, also have a panic button which I recommend you to have it.
It's called "APP CDMX"
(color in the map does not matter, they represent the dominant political party)

I would recommend you Tinder desu, have tried "Showaround" and a lot of people charge you on the hour, I'd show you around for free though but we gotta keep anonymous, better get to know a couple of bitches and plan something, you can find cheap Airbnb in many decent areas and ask them to stay with you. Madero and Azcapotzcalco UNLESS you have a concrete plan with your local friends there, those areas can be dangerous for locals too.
Around Mexico City, is the state of Mexico, which is out of the question, don't go there until you come back to Mexico, if ever. Another state you could visit which is safer is Yucatán. That would be good to go with American friends or family, because moving around with locals can be a little bit harder. Wouldn't recommend on your first travel.
Depending on what you like, but a local usually can be fine with 200MXN a day on expenses while going out, I'd recommend you to always have around 500MXN on cash and carry your credit card, if you go to Hooters or so, you end up spending around 600MXN, so you use your card for that instead of cash, because cash is still the norm around here, public transport in the city relies mostly on a universal card that you can add money to and move around with it, some buses still need you to pay with cash (6 MXN) but I don't think you will ever get on those while you're here.
I don't know what kind of expenses you would require. But I recently went to a party and spent 500MXN in drinks and food, got to know a chick, went to a motel that was 350MXN a night and took the metro back home for 5MXN, also bought water (1L for 15MXN). So around 45 bucks for a good night of fun.

And there is a lot of free entertainment too.
